Corbyn&#39;s decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
Corbyn&#39;s spokesman said he had &quot;stood respectfully silent&quot; and that he recognized &quot;the bravery of the Royal Air Force in Britain&#39;s air war.&quot;
A member of Corbyn&#39;s shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told BBC Two&#39;s Newsnight that he would have called on the Labor leader to sing the national anthem despite his belief that the House of Commons should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to be part of Corbyn&#39;s inner circle, citing differences over the economy, defense and foreign affairs. Originally, less than a sixth of the parliamentary party supported him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says that line differences regarding the party&#39;s position in the European Union and the government&#39;s aid ceiling have also &quot;piled up&quot; within the Labor Party since Corbyn&#39;s appointment.
Corbyn told a meeting of the Confederation of Trade Unions that Labor is proposing an amendment that would remove the entire cap.
Hours later, shadow government work and pensions secretary Smith said the party had been &quot;quite clear&quot; that they were only opposing the government&#39;s plans to lower the cap from £26,000 to £23,000.
Corbyn will be the fifth Labor leader David Cameron has faced in the last decade he has been leader of the Conservative Party.
The leader of the Labor Party has promised a new approach to politics and now says that he has &quot;crowdsourced&quot; ideas for questions to the Prime Minister, and received more than 30,000 suggestions.
Corbyn, the MP for Islington North, has said that the nature of the Prime Minister&#39;s question hours is too confrontational and that he intends to refrain from both witty words and barbs, promising instead to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges of young people.
Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle, the shadow financial secretary, will stand in for him during Question Time when Corbyn is not attending - such as when Cameron is abroad.
Corbyn has also suggested that other peers could also sometimes be allowed to use the floor, and has said he has approached the Speaker of the House of Commons, John Bercow, about the matter.
When Cameron took office in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the kind of political theater often associated with prime ministerial question hours, but he later admitted he had failed.
Since they began to be televised in 1990, Prime Minister&#39;s Question Hour has been an important measure of a leader&#39;s judgement, his control of the House of Commons, and his standing with other MPs, although critics have criticized Question Hour for having become nothing more than a laughingstock that calls for far-reaching reforms.
