Metcash is launching a grassroots campaign against Aldi&#39;s entry into the sector
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA stores from Aldi&#39;s onslaught in South and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a grassroots campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million attack by Aldi.
Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers and the first store early next year in South and Western Australia, which will include up to 120 stores. At the same time, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local grocers and building the IGA brand through mainstream and social media marketing and events such as the Adelaide show.
IGA retailers and stockists have jumped on board, with brands such as Dunsborough-based ice cream maker Simmo&#39;s offering tastings in IGA stores, and store owners selling discounted tickets to Australian rules football matches to regular customers.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details about its defense strategy on September 29 when the food, alcohol and hardware wholesaler holds its annual investor strategy day.
The stakes are high, as South and Western Australia together account for nearly 30 per cent of Metcash&#39;s IGA store territory, with higher profit margins than Metcash&#39;s Eastern States IGA network.
Shoppers in South and Western Australia are notoriously niche, and IGA retailers have a much larger market share there than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland: more than 30 per cent in the South and 24 per cent in the West, compared to 14 per cent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will capture about 5 percent of the grocery market in the two states within 12 months of opening the first stores. Turnover comes from all operators, but mainly from independent retailers.
In a report this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in annual sales and Metcash could lose $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in the South and 30 in the West next year, generating sales of $500 and $600 million in these regions.
The loss of food and grocery sales and volumes in Metcash&#39;s high fixed cost base could cost Metcash about $13 million in lost operating profit before interest and tax, Kierath said.
Meanwhile, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states mainly to Aldi and Coles, despite a recent Roy Morgan study finding that IGA&#39;s customers were the most loyal of all.
Morgan Stanley believes Metcash&#39;s food and grocery sales will fall 3.8 percent in 2016; 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, so that its market share will decrease from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent in 2020.
Last week, Hamish Douglass, manager of a leading investment fund and founder of Magellan Financial Group, said at a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash could &quot;quite possibly be lost in a decade&quot;.
Metcash has declined to respond publicly to Douglass&#39; comments.
However, it is understood that a Metcash board member contacted Douglass last week.
IGA&#39;s market share has fallen from 18% to 14% since 2010, and revenue from Metcash&#39;s food and grocery business, which supplies products to around 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen 43% since 2012. This indicates a reduction in the debt financing of operations when sales and margins are under pressure.
But the wholesaler stands firm, investing more than $150 million a year in bringing prices on hundreds of items a week in line with Coles and Woolworths, helping IGA retailers renovate stores by adding faster-growing fresh food, and introducing a better selection of private label products.
Metcash chief executive Ian Morrice says price cuts and store improvements have boosted appeal, and he hopes the wholesaler will return to profit growth in 2017 for the first time in four years.
