This is what happens when the US Federal Reserve raises interest rates
There will be an interest rate hike, and the bull market will crash, bond yields will rise and the economy will go into recession.
This we know.
What we don&#39;t know is how long all this will take or how long it will last.
The past doesn&#39;t give much help in terms of timing, when it comes specifically to the economy.
The onset of the recession has sometimes lasted only 11 months after the first withdrawal, sometimes it has gone as long as 86 months.
The US Federal Reserve&#39;s aggressiveness in raising interest rates has often, though not always, been a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
That is why the officials of the US central bank have emphasized so strongly that investors should not focus on when interest rates will start to be raised, but mainly on the development curve of the time leading to the normalization of the situation.
There are indeed several variables in the equation.
In the end, however, market participants may find that all the fuss related to the interest rate hike has been exaggerated.
&quot;The central bank&#39;s first rate hike since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted in some circles as the end of the &#39;cheap money&#39; era,&quot; said Julian Jessop, chief global economist at Capital Economics, in a message to clients.
Instead, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to normal, albeit still low, levels to be the kind of disruptive shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there are no effects.
Below is a look at how some areas of the economy will react based on past developments:
As the market has seen in the past month or so, waiting for an interest rate hike can make the situation unstable.
When the increase becomes a reality, the effect is not quite so dramatic.
&quot;It appears that returns on capital tend to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first hike, again potentially reflecting a lag in monetary policy,&quot; Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after a central bank hike.
Specifically, over the past 35 years or so, the market tends to be in a strong uptrend of around 14% approaching the hike, 250 days after that it&#39;s fairly flat (average up 2.6%), and normalcy has been reached after 500 days with average returns over the last six in the cycle 14.4 percent, according to a recent analysis by Nuveen Asset Management&#39;s chief capital strategist Bob Doll, published in Barron&#39;s magazine.
According to Deutsche Bank, the impact on stocks is usually clearer in the later phase of the hike cycle, when yields start to decline.
Recessions are part of economic life, but interest rate hikes often promote their arrival.
In the current situation, the central bank is facing certain challenges that did not exist before, and which may accelerate the recession.
This is especially the case with gross domestic product, which will be closest to its all-time low before the central bank raises interest rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, in the 118 withdrawals made since 1950, nominal annual GDP has only twice been below 4.5 percent.
While the number was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few believe it will last after the third quarter has advanced 1.5 percent, according to the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta.
Raising interest rates in such a fragile economic environment can be risky and raises the question of &quot;is this time different&quot;, Deutsche Bank stated.
Market participants have been bracing for a Fed rate hike all year, with everyone looking ahead to this week&#39;s Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and financial experts believe the committee may approve the hike at this meeting, futures trading predicts only a 25 percent chance.
&quot;Our research shows that since 1950, all expansionary cycles so far have occurred in supercycles of increasing leverage, in which GDP has surpassed its pre-recession peak very quickly after the recovery has begun,&quot; the report says.
In contrast, there has been an exceptionally slow recovery from the recession that has been the worst of the observation period.
In the current cycle, the central bank has waited by far the longest for the end of the last recession: the record has been 35 months, and now it is already in its 74th month.
Fixed income has also been volatile as the market waits for an interest rate hike, and the pattern is somewhat similar to the observations made on capital.
The main difference is that when the central bank changes its policy, its effects are seen faster in bonds than in stocks.
The direction of bond yields seems to change immediately at the first hike/cut of the cycle.
At the end of the hike cycle, bond yields will immediately drop,” Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab strategists believe that rising interest rates will cause longer- and shorter-dated bond yields to converge, thus flattening the yield curve.
High-yield bonds often outperform in such a situation, although &quot;we&#39;re still cautious about looking for yield,&quot; Schwab fixed income analyst Kathy Jones said in an analysis.
Surprisingly, Jones believes the market has already adjusted to the central bank&#39;s policy expectations.
&quot;In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are several signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,&quot; he wrote.
Short-term interest rates are high, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have increased, and volatility has increased - all these are characteristic of the market when the central bank has tightened its policy.
In general, companies whose business operations are primarily located in the United States will benefit when interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with a lot of debt perform worse when the rise in the value of the dollar makes their products more expensive on the world market and their debt becomes more expensive than what they have to finance.
&quot;History shows that &#39;quality&#39; stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months after the first rate hike,&quot; Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report to clients.
Companies with strong turnover outperformed companies with weak turnover by an average of five percentage points after the increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high return on capital and low volatility stocks outperformed lower quality companies. The average of the former was 4 (percentage points) and the latter 3 (percentage points).
Debt becomes a big problem.
Those companies with a lot of floating-rate debt stand to lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of stock market speculation, consumers also have the opportunity to benefit from the increase in the value of the dollar.
Savers may also benefit from higher returns, although experts disagree on how quickly the impact will be felt.
