&quot;Sound genetics&quot; makes it possible to control brain cells using sound waves
The video shows how nematodes change direction as soon as a sound impulse hits them.
Scientists have bred worms with genetically engineered nervous systems to be controlled by bursts of sound waves.
The tiny nematodes change direction as soon as they are hit by a sound impulse that is too high for the human ear to hear.
The impulses work by turning on genetically engineered motor neurons with membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
