The researchers said the worms show the new method, called sonic genetics, works. In it, ultrasound can be used to activate certain brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation. It is an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are delivered to people&#39;s brains to treat Parkinson&#39;s disease.
Nematodes don&#39;t normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when they were surrounded by a liquid with microscopic bubbles, that changed.
He discovered that the bubbles amplified the ultrasound waves, which then travel inside the worms.
Amplified ultrasound waves affect TRP-4 ion channels, structures found in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells attached to them, according to a report published in the journal Nature Communications.
To make ultrasound-guided nematodes, Chalasani genetically engineered the worms so that some of their motor neurons have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani applied ultrasound to the engineered worms, the microbubbles amplified the sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they turned on the engineered motor neurons.
The method shares some of the same features as optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light pulses.
However, Chalasani says that using sonogenetics may have some advantages over optogenetics.
Unlike light, which must be sent along an optical fiber to the desired location inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
&quot;We believe that using gene therapy and a therapeutic virus, it may be possible to make target human neurons momentarily respond to an ultrasound signal for certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting,&quot; Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
