In the forests surrounding the center, men traveling without their families stay in tents, sheds and abandoned cars, which everyone has managed to find or build.
Families who, for one reason or another, have not submitted an asylum application to Serbia also live in the forest.
Some also stay in private apartments, but that is an open secret.
Among the foresters, Goran finds most of his customers.
These are often exhausted - the route through the Balkans requires a large number of border crossings and weeks of walking in difficult terrain, often in mountainous areas and in the dark.
When they finally arrive in the Bogovaða area, a major human trafficking hub, the people are dead tired.
Goran&#39;s passengers are mainly Syrians, Afghans, Pakistanis, Iraqis and Kurds.
The best customers are the Syrians, he says in the book.
&quot;They say their case once and that&#39;s enough,&quot; Goran praises.
According to him, Africans are trying to bargain.
Goran doesn&#39;t like that.
Idiot Idiot Idiot all the way.
First we agree on a price of, for example, 300 euros, then they lower it to 200 and finally offer 150.
Goran emphasizes that he is a nice and kind-hearted man.
I&#39;m not interested in money.
I&#39;m just doing my job and helping people,&quot; he says in the book.
Goran says that he works cheaper than others and that he only charges 50 euros per person for the ride to the Hungarian border.
The journey is three hundred kilometers, most of it comfortably on the highway.
Colleagues are reportedly asking for three or four times the price.
Goran earns around 50,000 euros a year.
It&#39;s not a big sum for a smuggler, but in Serbia it&#39;s quite a nice annual income.
Serbia has ordered that taxis may not transport migrants 12 kilometers closer to the Hungarian border.
Goran doesn&#39;t care about that: he knows the roads and Shortcuts and takes his passenger a kilometer away from the border.
Then he points his customers in the right direction and storms off.
In the work of Laupeu
The 35-year-old Congolese man is called Missionary, and it&#39;s not just a nickname.
He actually has a Protestant church in Kampala, the capital of Uganda, where many believers who have fled the Congo attend, as well as a small center that helps Congolese child refugees.
In addition to preaching, the Missionary runs a smuggling business where people are moved from the Congo to Europe.
He considers himself to be doing a work of mercy.
Looking good is important to a missionary.
He shines his shoes several times a day and makes sure that the elastic band of his white ankle boots peeks elegantly from under the low waist of his jeans.
The missionary is proud of his new Mercedes, SUV and three motorcycles.
When the Missionary is not preaching, he is organizing people from the Congo to Uganda and on to Europe.
The customer initially calls one of the Missionary&#39;s five phone numbers.
He advises that you should arrive at the border in the morning, hide the money carefully and sneak among the traders crossing the border.
In order to get the status of asylum seeker or refugee, the Ugandan authorities must be told that they are from, for example, the war zones of North Kivu, and that they have had to flee their home from violence.
Often it is true, but if not, the Missionary arranges a new identity for the client.
The old identity card will be destroyed and another one will be obtained in its place.
The Missionary&#39;s contacts in the Ugandan police will help with that.
After that, the client is directed to the same place where real asylum seekers go: to the asylum application procedure, to non-governmental organizations, finally to the UN refugee agency UNHCR.
The missionary knows bureaucracy because he himself came to Uganda as a refugee.
He invoices for each step separately: submitting an application to the Ugandan police costs about one hundred euros, handling documents for a humanitarian organization costs about 150, and the process of moving to a European country, for example, costs 4,500-7,000 euros.
Foil and ice cubes
Tom is a budding smuggler, a former drug courier.
An Irishman in his forties is on duty on the French coast in Calais, where his job is to load people onto trucks bound for Britain.
He has the help of an Afghani living in London, a French taxi driver and dozens of truck drivers who may not even know that they are in the human smuggling business.
At night, Tom and the taxi driver pick up their customers, usually 2-3 people, somewhere near the center of Calais.
They drive the A26 motorway and try to avoid the police.
If the police stopped the car on the highway, Tom and the driver would go straight to jail for organizing illegal immigration.
That&#39;s not what Tom wants, he&#39;s been in jail for seven years for drugs.
The taxi stops, Tom and his customers run across the highway to a rest stop where the drivers sleep before continuing across the channel to the Brits.
Tom chooses a suitable truck - it is necessary to make sure that it is on its way to England and not, say, Holland - and cuts the safety wire of the protective cover.
It must be done quietly so the drivers don&#39;t wake up.
Sometimes the driver is involved in the plot, but then the hassle is more expensive.
When the route is clear, Tom wraps his client in aluminum foil, the same kind that is wrapped around a roast or baked potato in the kitchen.
That should prevent the police thermal scanner from spotting the hider.
Some use a sleeping bag filled with ice for the same purpose.
Tom leaves his client in the truck and leaves the place, hoping that the driver won&#39;t catch any hitchhikers at least before Britain.
King of Smugglers
Muammer Küçük is one of the world&#39;s most famous human smugglers.
