The US Fed will next try to tighten monetary policy
The next recession in the United States will begin in less than a year at the earliest, but more likely within three years, after the country&#39;s central bank, the Fed, starts raising its interest rates again after a long time.
And in the financial market, the downturn starts before the next recession.
The Fed has hinted that it will start raising interest rates possibly as early as this week and by the end of the year at the latest.
Therefore, the next recession can hit the fastest by next autumn and the financial markets will be the price rhythm before then.
Or at least that&#39;s what will happen if the world&#39;s largest economy and financial markets operate as they have been doing - and if they react to the Fed&#39;s tightening of the money taps as they have in the past.
These are the conclusions reached by Jim Reid, Nick Burns and Seb Barker, market research strategists of the German bank Deutsche Bank in London, in their extensive study of long-term market and economic cycles.
The bank distributed the more than 60-page Long-Term Asset Return Study research report to its major international customers last week.
The strategists who wrote the study and report do not believe they know when exactly the Fed will start raising interest rates or what will happen in the economy and markets after that.
Instead, they use the hard facts and calculations of economic statistics to show how the economy and markets have behaved in the past during and after Fed rate hikes.
In addition to historical observations, they examine which key variables of the economy and financial markets are now in the same or different pattern than at the time of previous interest rate increases - and what may result from that.
It becomes clear that both the economy and the financial markets are now in a worse condition to withstand a rise in interest rates than at any time since the 1950s.
Maybe not even a year until the beginning of the recession
The leaders who decide on the Fed&#39;s monetary policy and its current tone have been hinting throughout last summer and early autumn that the time is starting to be ripe for raising interest rates.
The first interest rate hike in more than nine years could come as early as this week.
The matter will be resolved between Wednesday and Thursday, when the so-called open market committee of the Fed&#39;s executive board gathers to decide on the matter in its two-day meeting.
The last time the Fed raised its so-called Fed funds policy rate was in June 2006.
That was the end of exactly two years of relatively regular but small rate hikes of 0.25 percentage points at a time, with which the Fed raised its interest rate from 1.25 percent to 5.25 percent.
The symptoms of the financial markets began in 2007 with the difficulties of the US&#39;s riskiest housing financing, and a year later the financial crisis erupted into a global doomsday nightmare.
The big recession hit in 2009.
Last time, the serious setbacks in the financial markets and the real economy started more slowly than it has typically happened after previous interest rate hikes by the Fed.
Correspondingly, the trials were harder and harsher than ever since the depression of the 1930s.
Deutsche&#39;s strategists have sifted through the ups and downs of the world&#39;s largest economies and the ups and downs of the financial markets since 1950 and in some places since the beginning of the 19th century.
They have been explaining the Fed&#39;s interest rate hikes and their economic and financial effects since the 1950s.
From the first rate hike to the start of the recession, the quickest time has been less than a year, most often less than three years, and on average less than three and a half years.
The price rise in the financial markets has ended within a year or two after the start of the Fed&#39;s interest rate hikes.
The Fed has alternately raised and alternately lowered its key interest rate since the early 1950s by a dozen cycles of varying sizes.
Each time has differed in some respects from the others, and there are relatively few multipliers in the review, so based on them, it is hardly possible to conclude anything definite about the effects of the next interest rate hikes.
The strategists remind us that this time many things are different.
And not just better.
Interest rates too low for too long
Even with decades of research, the decisive causes of the financial crisis, let alone the culprits, cannot be found out beyond doubt.
But three points about the reasons that led to the crisis and increased its destructive power should be clear to some extent beyond doubt:
1) In the 2000s, the Fed, the ECB of the euro area and other major central banks kept their key interest rates too low for too long.
They patched up the traces of the techno bubble, and at the same time grew the next one.
2) The already excessive amount of debt accumulated in various parts of the financial and real economy over the decades grew even larger under the influence of the central banks&#39; excessively loose monetary policy.
The largest debt bubble in economic history up to that point was born.
3) In particular, the crazy-cheap debt financing packed almost without restraint into the financial economy inflated the largest price bubbles in the economic history up to that point in most areas of the financial market, from shares to real estate, bonds and commodities.
It is also unlikely that there will be a very harsh dispute that the financial markets, which had soared to heights based on increasingly complicated debt levers, were in a rare dangerous and unstable mess when the Fed and other central banks last drove interest rates up.
Financial structures tuned to debt levers, let alone valuation bubbles, only lasted their time after the interest rate hikes had started and the costs of debt financing had started to rise.
The risks materialized as the financial crisis, and the Great Recession followed.
Bigger bubble and more debt
Deutsche&#39;s strategists don&#39;t guess what will happen next, but they give a reason to think by mentioning things like the following, for example:
1) The Fed and other major central banks have now kept their monetary policy even easier for even longer than before the financial crisis.
If interest rates were too low for too long before the crisis, now they have been even lower for even longer.
2) Getting into debt hasn&#39;t been crazy cheap for a long time like it was ten years ago, but now debt money is literally cheaper than free money at its lowest point.
Therefore, the debt burden of the financial and real economy has not eased, but now in different parts of the economy there is a much heavier debt load than before the financial crisis or at any time before.
3) The liquidity issued by the central banks, which is more flowing and cheaper than before, has for the most part remained in the financial market and has made key securities and asset classes more expensive, whether at the peak before the financial crisis or never.
And the strategists don&#39;t just lighten the mood with financial market warning signs, they also point out that even the US economy has not yet recovered from the financial crisis and the heaviest recession in decades to the pattern it has been in before.
The eurozone economy has hardly recovered at all.
In other words, the real economy is in an unusually weak condition, but correspondingly, the pressures and risks of the financial markets are incomparably greater than before the financial crisis, when the Fed next starts to tighten its money taps more tightly.
Perhaps the picture of the future of Albert Edwards, the strategist of the French bank Societe Generale, is not as strange as it might seem.
For quite some time now, he has been coaching the bank&#39;s international investor clients for the following complete translations of the Fed:
First the Fed raises interest rates, then the financial bubbles burst - and soon it will be time for the Fed to rush to put out the financial fires with even bigger QE money injections.
