For two days this week, the policymakers of the US Federal Reserve will sit around a huge mahogany table in a long-awaited meeting to decide whether the time has come to raise the key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
At one end of the central bank&#39;s ornate, two-story boardroom is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the nation&#39;s economic interests above all else.
Congress has placed the Federal Reserve on the shoulders of a dual responsibility: they must maximize US employment and keep prices stable.
However, since the Great Depression, central bankers have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
It is this third requirement that may be the decisive factor in the decision to be announced on Thursday, which is so strict that it cannot even be predicted. The decision on whether the US economy is ready to be weaned off the record-breaking stimulus that the short-term interest rate, which remained at almost zero until the end of 2008, has brought.
While most data points to steady economic growth, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may have made already wary central bank officials more nervous about further volatility. We are afraid of what the effect would be if the federal funds rate reference value were raised even by a quarter of a percentage point.
&quot;Understandably, the labor market and inflation are the first and most important things that are monitored,&quot; states Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Brokerage Stifel Nicolaus &amp; Co.
&quot;However, I believe that if they are looking for a justification for leaving the interest rate unchanged, the increased uncertainty in the world market is a valid enough reason to wait a little longer,&quot; he says.
No consensus has been reached on the central bank&#39;s decision, which is already creating nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent survey by Bloomberg, about half of economic experts predict that interest rates will rise this week.
The financial market, on the other hand, expects the central bank to delay the withdrawal, because according to the key indicator, the chance of growth is only about 30 percent.
This suggests a fall in the securities market if the central bank raises the rate, unless the decision-makers succeed in softening the blow by promising that the next increase will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average index rose 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, with the new figure being 16,599.85.
The recovery was brought about by the expectation that the central bank will keep the level unchanged this week, says John Lonski, chief economic expert at Moody&#39;s Capital Markets Research Group.
&quot;It&#39;s surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now,&quot; he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, &quot;they have to put a lot of effort into their policy to support the financial markets so that they don&#39;t panic.&quot;
Other experts argue that the increased level would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the central bank would act.
Just a month ago, it looked like the central bank was on its way to raising interest rates by a quarter percentage point this month, taking the first small step toward the slow tightening of monetary conditions that would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that she expects the level to rise this year, despite the Liberals calling for more economic development in their complaints.
Although the creation of new jobs slowed down in August, labor market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest figure in seven years and close to the level that the central bank considers the limit of full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of picking up.
Although inflation is still below the central bank&#39;s 2 percent annual target, according to the central bank&#39;s decision makers, the main reason for this is the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy &quot;can survive even higher interest rates and also needs them considering the tight situation in the labor market&quot;, says Ian Shepherdson, chief economic expert at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average index fell by up to 16 percent from its May record, as investors feared that China&#39;s slowing economy would also slow down global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow is now almost 10 percent below its peak in May.
For the central bank&#39;s decision-makers, the market turmoil is an additional factor in the complex equation that tells when the interest rate should be raised.
&quot;Without these financial market events and recent weeks of news about the weakness of the Chinese economy, policymakers would be tightening at this meeting,&quot; said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
Now, he predicts that policymakers will wait at least a month to get a better idea of the impact.
&quot;The possible effects on the US economy are still quite unclear, and they don&#39;t have much information at their disposal regarding the consequences of the events in China,&quot; states Oliner.
The well-being of the international economy is not the main concern of the central bank, so in principle it should not affect decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve Bank has become the world&#39;s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been immense.
In 2013, then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke&#39;s suggestion that the central bank might &quot;tape&quot; the money supply caused upheaval in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to follow developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank&#39;s decision-making process is &quot;more art than science,&quot; says Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at asset management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that &quot;the central bank has historically overreacted to financial market movements that have appeared to be disconnected from economic fundamentals.&quot;
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for a rate hike, and Lacker, a voting member of the committee, cites the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The Asian financial crisis caused the central bank to cut its benchmark by 0.75 percentage points over three meetings &quot;despite its limited, discernible impact on US economic growth,&quot; Lacker says.
A year later, the central bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should prioritize financial stability only during a major crisis, such as when the market crashed in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England&#39;s interest rate-setting committee.
The latest turmoil doesn&#39;t even come close to that level, Posen states.
&quot;No one wants to be in a situation where interest rate hikes are feared because the market will get upset,&quot; says Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a dual requirement and does not mention financial stability. As long as this is the case, I don&#39;t think they should anticipate it.
