It was not immediately clear why rubber bullets, known to kill but traditionally used as a less dangerous alternative, appeared to have caused so many deaths.
The clash was the latest in weeks of violent protests across Nepal&#39;s southern plains, where members of an ethnic group called the Madhesi say new provinces created under the proposed new constitution will erode their political influence.
There have also been protests in western Nepal when the Tharus group demands their own state.
Since August 10, at least 40 people have died in violent clashes, 11 of whom have been police officers.
At the time, the four main parties signed an agreement dividing the country into provinces - a big step towards a new constitution, but a very controversial issue in Nepal, which has had a central government for centuries.
A new constitution has been planned since 2008, but lawmakers accelerated the process after a devastating earthquake in April killed thousands of people.
Lawmakers have been voting on clauses in a draft constitution in Kathmandu this week, and officials have said the new charter could be approved by Sunday.
