Weight loss surgery can help mildly obese diabetics
The benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after bariatric surgery than those treated with methods other than surgery.
&quot;It takes a long time to get mortality data,&quot; says Dr. Robin Blackstone. He is a weight loss surgery specialist who wrote the editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
In weight loss or bariatric surgeries, different methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the subjects in the study were morbidly obese, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
BMI, i.e. the ratio of weight to height, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If a BMI is over 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if a person&#39;s BMI is over 30, they are considered obese.
You can calculate your own BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Taiwan&#39;s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery and gastric reduction, with drug treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of those who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of those who were treated by means other than surgery remained roughly the same at 29.
Of the people who underwent surgery, 36 percent of the diabetes was cured completely and 28 percent partially.
In comparison, in the drug-treated group, diabetes was completely cured by only 1 percent and partially by about 2 percent.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and &quot;bad&quot; LDL cholesterol &quot;were generally better in the surgery group,&quot; the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored the patients&#39; blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect long-term blood sugar levels.
The hemoglobin A1c value should remain below 7 percent, the researchers write.
Postoperative hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
In the medical treatment group, however, it remained stable at around 8 percent.
However, this better &quot;glycemic control,&quot; as reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce mortality over five years, say lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results between two different types of surgery.
At the fifth year, when compared to the gastric bypass group, the gastric bypass group had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), reduced their body mass index more (7.4 and 5.1), reduced their hemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1 percent and 2.1 percent), and were more likely to achieve complete diabetes remission (46.9 percent and 16.7 percent).
Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenix says that while the study doesn&#39;t show survival or surgery after five years, there is research from Sweden where surgery led to longer lives in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people who underwent weight-loss surgery were 29 percent less likely to die over a 15-year period when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
Although the new study doesn&#39;t show an improvement in survival for surgery patients, Blackstone says the results are encouraging for people with a BMI under 35 who are interested in surgery.
&quot;The research results are decisive precisely in that they show that the surgery is safe for a group with a lower body mass index,&quot; and does not involve an increased risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously when a patient&#39;s BMI is between 27 and 30.
&quot;I think we&#39;re waiting too long to take this seriously,&quot; he says.
I believe that once a person has accumulated these genetic changes that permanently prepare their body for obesity and diabetes, it is very difficult to reverse the situation.
