There are videos on YouTube of teenagers drinking disinfectant to get a cheap high.
According to reports, teenagers have been mixing disinfectant with alcoholic mouthwash to make a stronger drink.
The pleasant smells of the disinfectant may attract younger children.
&quot;The child doesn&#39;t think this is bad for him,&quot; Lopez said.
Many of the more interesting (handmade) ones are the ones with added fragrance.
There are strawberry, grape and orange scented disinfectants that are very attractive to children.
Hand sanitizer can contain anything between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in small children, only a few injections are needed for alcohol poisoning.
&quot;It&#39;s really concentrated alcohol,&quot; Mr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Poison Information Center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
So you wouldn&#39;t leave a shot of whiskey sitting on the table, but leave the hand sanitizer in plain sight, and if the kids are interested, it&#39;s a quick way to drink a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell is a six-year-old girl who not long ago swallowed just four squirts of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school and was taken to the emergency room for treatment.
Her blood-alcohol level was .179, twice the adult drunken driving limit, said emergency room physician Chris Ritchey, who treated the girl at Gwinnet Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was slurring her words and unable to walk when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children&#39;s hospital for signs of a brain injury, as the alcohol caused the girl to fall and hit her head, Ritchey said.
&quot;It was really scary,&quot; Nhaijah&#39;s mother, Ortoria Scott, told CNN.
The situation could have been fatal for my child.
Lopez has recommended that parents and teachers use alcohol-free products or disinfectant wipes and move the disinfectant out of children&#39;s reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants have been linked to deaths.
In 2013, two Ontario women died after ingesting hand sanitizer that contained a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials believe the product contained methanol, a deadly substance, and not ethyl alcohol, which was reported as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-graders in upstate New York planned to poison their &quot;mean&quot; teacher by spreading a bacterial poison in the classroom, according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand sanitizer and banned it from her class.
