It&#39;s striking how similar depictions don&#39;t exist in the series, especially considering that men&#39;s need to open up is more desperate than ever, and the suicide rate among young men is higher than it&#39;s been in fifteen years.
In 2013, suicide was the leading cause of death for men aged 20-45 in the UK, and is three times more common in men than in women.
In an attempt to tackle the problem, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) declared 2015 the Year of Men. The goal was to challenge the culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of facing this challenge.
A recent study involved more than 2,000 middle school and high school age students who showed symptoms of depression. According to the study, a person&#39;s chance of recovery doubled if a high enough percentage of his friends were &quot;in good spirits&quot;.
Similarly, for those who were not depressed, the probability of possible mental health problems was halved if they had mentally healthy friends.
But for friendship to work, it must first be available.
In this age of communication through social media, style overrides content and the immediacy of a response is often more important than meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have redoubled the need to appear strong, happy and successful, when in reality isolation reigns supreme.
This superficial success is dominated by values that psychologists call extrinsic: money, image, social status. All of this comes at the expense of inner values—the inner longing for personal growth and friendship—that have a deeper impact on our mental health.
And as a billionaire video game developer recently explained, money really doesn&#39;t buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was precisely that it turned this focus on its head.
Neither character was defined by their work, but rather by their personalities, which stood out clearly in their interactions as friends.
Joey and Chandler&#39;s numerous hugs, moments in comfortable chairs watching football, Ross missing Rachel - the humor of these came from the knowledge that yes, men can relate to all of this, even if they are often hesitant to fully explore their feelings.
As a Samaritans volunteer explained to me: ...&quot;listening to people who are depressed and suicidal, I&#39;ve really understood how even the smallest interaction with a friend can make you feel better.&quot;
Often men who contact us feel that they cannot talk to friends.
The old idea of &quot;getting over it&quot; is strong, as is the feeling that if you open up about problems, you will be seen as weak.
Frendit is one of those series that comes to mind when I&#39;m trying to provide more long-term means of survival.
It highlighted the small moments of friendship between men.
While my neutral, outsider position on the other end of the phone helps people in times of despair, long-term support comes from a close, personal network of family and friends.
So if you&#39;re attending Comedy Central&#39;s FriendsFest this weekend, and all the sets have been redesigned to celebrate, why not take your friends out for coffee at Central Perk.
Or, better yet, if you see someone lonely at Starbucks, smile and say hello.
